.TH "IFCFG\-DUMMY" "5" "April 30, 2024" "wicked" "Wicked User Manual"
.SH NAME
ifcfg\-dummy \- Dummy interface configuration
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[CR]/etc/sysconfig/network/ifcfg\-*\f[R]
.SH Dummy Interfaces
To setup a dummy interface you either need a configuration file with the
\f[CR]DUMMY=yes\f[R] variable set or one using a config file name
\f[B]ifcfg\-dummyX\f[R] (e.g.\ ifcfg\-dummy0).
.TP
\f[CR]DUMMY <yes|no>\f[R]
This option must be set to \f[B]yes\f[R] to identify this configuration
type as dummy, regardless of the configuration file name.
.TP
\f[CR]BOOTPROTO\f[R]
may be set to \[lq]none\[rq] or \[lq]static\[rq].
Note that \[lq]dhcp\[rq] and others are not supported.
See also \f[CR]man ifcfg\f[R] and \f[CR]man routes\f[R] for details.
.SH EXAMPLE
Example \f[CR]ifcfg\-<name>\f[R] config file for a dummy interface:
.IP
.EX
DUMMY=yes
STARTMODE=auto
BOOTPROTO=static
IPADDR=10.0.0.100/24
.EE
